# Wine, Cheese & Gastronomy — Wine Regions

# ── France ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "wine:region:france" "Wine-producing country; home of AOC/AOP system, Bordeaux, Burgundy, Champagne and more. World's most influential wine nation by regulation and prestige."
def "wine:region:bordeaux" "Major AOC wine region in southwest France at Gironde estuary. Renowned for Cabernet Sauvignon and Merlot blends. Home to classified châteaux system (1855 Classification)."
def "wine:region:medoc" "Sub-region of Bordeaux on the left bank of the Gironde. Produces Cabernet Sauvignon-dominant blends; home to Pauillac, Saint-Estèphe, Margaux appellations."
def "wine:region:saint_emilion" "Sub-region of Bordeaux on the right bank of the Dordogne. Merlot and Cabernet Franc dominant. UNESCO World Heritage Site; home to Pétrus and Cheval Blanc."
def "wine:region:pomerol" "Small sub-region of Bordeaux, right bank. Produces rich, plummy Merlot-based wines. Home to Pétrus, one of the world's most expensive wines. No formal classification."
def "wine:region:sauternes" "Sub-region of Bordeaux producing famous sweet wines via Botrytis cinerea (noble rot). Sémillon, Sauvignon Blanc, Muscadelle blend. Château d'Yquem is premier cru supérieur."
def "wine:region:burgundy" "AOC region in east-central France. World benchmark for Pinot Noir and Chardonnay. Strict terroir-based classification: Grand Cru → Premier Cru → Village → Regional."
def "wine:region:cote_de_nuits" "Northern sub-region of Burgundy's Côte d'Or. Predominantly red Pinot Noir. Home to grands crus: Romanée-Conti, Chambertin, Musigny, Clos de Vougeot."
def "wine:region:cote_de_beaune" "Southern sub-region of Burgundy's Côte d'Or. Famous for white Chardonnay (Montrachet, Meursault) and red Pinot Noir (Pommard, Volnay)."
def "wine:region:chablis" "Northernmost sub-region of Burgundy. Produces steely, mineral-driven Chardonnay without oak influence. Four quality levels: Petit Chablis, Chablis, Premier Cru, Grand Cru."
def "wine:region:champagne" "AOC region northeast of Paris. Only region legally producing Champagne via méthode champenoise. Chardonnay, Pinot Noir, Pinot Meunier. Centre at Reims and Épernay."
def "wine:region:alsace" "AOC region along Rhine River bordering Germany. Produces aromatic single-varietal whites: Riesling, Gewurztraminer, Pinot Gris, Muscat. Germanic bottle shapes, French philosophy."
def "wine:region:loire_valley" "Long AOC region along Loire River. Diverse styles: Muscadet (mouth), Sancerre/Pouilly-Fumé (Sauvignon Blanc), Vouvray (Chenin Blanc), Chinon (Cabernet Franc)."
def "wine:region:rhone_valley" "AOC region along Rhône River, divided North (Syrah, Viognier) and South (GSM blends). Key appellations: Hermitage, Côte-Rôtie, Châteauneuf-du-Pape, Gigondas."
def "wine:region:chateauneuf_du_pape" "Prestigious sub-region of Southern Rhône. Up to 18 permitted grape varieties. Known for rich Grenache-based reds and galets roulés (large smooth stones) that retain heat."
def "wine:region:languedoc_roussillon" "Largest wine-producing region in France by volume, Mediterranean coast. Historically bulk wine; now producing quality reds and whites. IGP Pays d'Oc is major category."
def "wine:region:provence" "AOC region in southeast France. World's leading producer of dry rosé wine. Appellations include Bandol (Mourvèdre), Cassis, Les Baux-de-Provence."

# ── Italy ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "wine:region:italy" "Wine-producing country; world's largest by volume. DOC/DOCG classification system. Twenty wine regions covering entire peninsula and islands. Enormous varietal diversity."
def "wine:region:tuscany" "Central Italian DOC/DOCG region. Home to Chianti, Brunello di Montalcino, Vino Nobile, Super Tuscans (IGT). Sangiovese is the dominant grape variety."
def "wine:region:chianti_classico" "DOCG sub-region within Tuscany between Florence and Siena. 100% Sangiovese (Grosso) required for Riserva and Gran Selezione. Black Rooster (Gallo Nero) symbol."
def "wine:region:brunello_di_montalcino" "DOCG sub-region in southern Tuscany. 100% Sangiovese Grosso (Brunello clone). Among Italy's most age-worthy reds; minimum aging 5 years before release."
def "wine:region:piedmont" "Northwestern Italian DOC/DOCG region bordering France and Switzerland. Home to Barolo, Barbaresco (Nebbiolo), Barbera d'Asti, Moscato d'Asti, Gavi."
def "wine:region:barolo" "DOCG sub-region in Piedmont Langhe hills. 100% Nebbiolo. 'King of Italian wines.' Minimum 3 years aging (5 for Riserva). Communes: La Morra, Barolo, Castiglione Falletto."
def "wine:region:barbaresco" "DOCG sub-region in Piedmont adjacent to Barolo. 100% Nebbiolo. 'Queen of Italian wines.' Less tannic and earlier drinking than Barolo. Communes: Barbaresco, Treiso, Neive."
def "wine:region:veneto" "Northeastern Italian DOC/DOCG region. Largest by volume. Home to Valpolicella, Amarone, Soave, Prosecco DOC, Bardolino. Verona is the wine capital."
def "wine:region:amarone" "DOCG sub-region within Valpolicella, Veneto. Corvina-based wine made from dried grapes (appassimento). Rich, powerful, 14-17% alcohol. Aged minimum 2 years (4 for Riserva)."
def "wine:region:soave" "DOC sub-region in Veneto east of Verona. Garganega-dominant white wine. Soave Classico zone has superior volcanic soils. Also produces Recioto di Soave (sweet)."
def "wine:region:prosecco_doc" "Large DOC zone in Veneto and Friuli producing sparkling wine from Glera grape. Charmat method (tank). Conegliano Valdobbiadene DOCG is the superior sub-zone."
def "wine:region:sicily" "Island region, southernmost Italian wine zone. Historically bulk; now fine wine. Nero d'Avola, Nerello Mascalese (Etna), Grillo, Catarratto, Marsala (fortified)."
def "wine:region:campania" "Southern Italian region. Indigenous varieties: Aglianico (Taurasi DOCG), Greco di Tufo, Fiano di Avellino. Volcanic soils from Vesuvius influence character."
def "wine:region:friuli" "Northeastern Italian region bordering Slovenia and Austria. Known for high-quality white wines: Friulano, Pinot Grigio, Ribolla Gialla. Also birthplace of modern orange wine."

# ── Spain ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "wine:region:spain" "Wine-producing country; third largest by area under vine. DO/DOCa classification. Diverse regions: Rioja, Ribera del Duero, Priorat, Rías Baixas. Tempranillo-dominant."
def "wine:region:rioja" "DOCa region in northern Spain along Ebro River. Spain's most recognised wine region. Tempranillo blends; aging categories: Joven, Crianza, Reserva, Gran Reserva."
def "wine:region:ribera_del_duero" "DO region on Duero River plateau, Castile. Tempranillo (called Tinto Fino). Rivals Rioja; high-altitude vineyards with extreme temperatures. Vega Sicilia is landmark estate."
def "wine:region:priorat" "DOCa region in Catalonia (one of two DOCa in Spain). Llicorella slate soils, low yields, old-vine Garnacha and Cariñena. Intense, concentrated wines. Renaissance since 1990s."
def "wine:region:rias_baixas" "DO region in Galicia, Atlantic northwest Spain. Albariño white wine. Granite soils, high rainfall. Pergola-trained vines. Seafood pairing region."
def "wine:region:jerez" "DO region in Andalucía producing Sherry (Jerez/Xérès/Sherry). Palomino Fino base grape; Solera aging system. Styles: Fino, Manzanilla, Amontillado, Oloroso, Pedro Ximénez."
def "wine:region:cava_do" "DO for Spanish sparkling wine made by traditional method (méthode champenoise). Primarily Catalonia (Penedès). Macabeo, Xarel-lo, Parellada grapes. Cava de Paraje Calificado is top tier."
def "wine:region:penedes" "DO region in Catalonia, centre of Cava production. Also still wines. Torres and other pioneers introduced international varieties; Xarel-lo becoming prestigious for still whites."

# ── Germany ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "wine:region:germany" "Wine-producing country. 13 Anbaugebiete (growing regions). Riesling is king. Prädikatswein quality scale: Kabinett → Spätlese → Auslese → Beerenauslese → TBA/Eiswein."
def "wine:region:mosel" "Anbaugebiet along Mosel, Saar, and Ruwer rivers. Steep slate slopes, Riesling dominant. Elegant, low-alcohol, high-acid style. Great Grosse Gewächse (GG) dry wines and late harvest."
def "wine:region:rheingau" "Anbaugebiet along Rhine east of Rüdesheim. 80% Riesling, 15% Spätburgunder (Pinot Noir). Historic region with Schloss Johannisberg, Kloster Eberbach. Full-bodied Riesling style."
def "wine:region:rheinhessen" "Germany's largest Anbaugebiet by area. Historically bulk wine (Liebfraumilch); now serious dry Riesling and Silvaner. Westhofen and Nierstein are premium sub-zones."
def "wine:region:pfalz" "Anbaugebiet south of Rheinhessen, warmer climate. Diverse varieties: Riesling, Grauburgunder, Weissburgunder. Germany's second-largest region; full-bodied, fruity styles."
def "wine:region:franken" "Anbaugebiet in Bavaria. Distinctive Bocksbeutel (flat-bottomed flask). Silvaner is the signature grape. Dry, earthy, food-friendly wines. Würzburg is the main city."
def "wine:region:ahr" "Germany's northernmost red wine Anbaugebiet. Specialises in Spätburgunder (Pinot Noir). Narrow valley with steep slate slopes. Small production, highly sought after."

# ── Portugal ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "wine:region:portugal" "Wine-producing country with unique indigenous varieties. DOC classification. Famous for Port, Vinho Verde, Douro reds, Alentejo. Touriga Nacional is flagship grape."
def "wine:region:douro" "DOC region along Douro River in northeastern Portugal. Schist soils, terraced vineyards. Produces Port (fortified) and world-class unfortified reds. UNESCO World Heritage."
def "wine:region:porto_doc" "DOC for Port wine, produced in Douro Valley. Fortified with grape spirit mid-fermentation. Styles: Ruby, Tawny, LBV, Vintage. Must be aged in Vila Nova de Gaia lodges."
def "wine:region:vinho_verde" "DOC in northwest Portugal (Minho). 'Green wine' — young, fresh, light, slightly effervescent. Alvarinho (Albariño) is premium single-varietal; blends also common."
def "wine:region:alentejo" "Large DOC region in southern Portugal. Warm continental climate. Full-bodied reds and modern whites. Aragonez (Tempranillo), Alicante Bouschet, Touriga Nacional blends."
def "wine:region:setubal" "Peninsula DOC south of Lisbon. Famous for Moscatel de Setúbal (fortified sweet Muscat). Sandy soils; some of oldest Muscat vines in the world."
def "wine:region:madeira_do" "DOC for Madeira wine produced on Madeira island. Unique estufagem heating process creates oxidative style. Four main varietals: Sercial, Verdelho, Bual, Malmsey. Virtually immortal wine."

# ── Other Europe ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "wine:region:austria_wachau" "Prestigious wine region in Lower Austria along Danube. Three quality tiers: Steinfeder, Federspiel, Smaragd. Grüner Veltliner and Riesling on steep terraced loess and gneiss slopes."
def "wine:region:tokaj_hungary" "Historic DOC region in northeastern Hungary. World's first classified wine region (1730). Furmint-based sweet Tokaji Aszú measured in puttonyos. 'Wine of kings, king of wines.'"
def "wine:region:santorini_pdo" "PDO region on volcanic Greek island of Santorini. Assyrtiko on ancient basket-trained vines (kouloura). Volcanic pumice soil. Exceptional mineral acidity and longevity. No irrigation needed."
def "wine:region:swiss_valais" "Major Swiss wine canton in upper Rhône Valley. Chasselas (Fendant), Pinot Noir (Dôle), Humagne, Cornalin grown on steep terraces. Most wines consumed domestically."

# ── USA ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "wine:region:usa" "Wine-producing country. AVA (American Viticultural Area) system. California dominant (90% of production); Oregon, Washington, New York also significant."
def "wine:region:napa_valley" "AVA in Napa County, California. USA's most prestigious wine region. Cabernet Sauvignon benchmark. 16 sub-AVAs including Stags Leap, Oakville, Rutherford, Mount Veeder."
def "wine:region:sonoma" "AVA in Sonoma County, California. Diverse climate zones: Russian River Valley (Pinot Noir, Chardonnay), Alexander Valley (Cabernet), Dry Creek (Zinfandel)."
def "wine:region:willamette_valley" "AVA in Oregon. World-class Pinot Noir and Pinot Gris. Cool, rainy maritime climate. Chehalem Mountains, Eola-Amity Hills, Dundee Hills are premium sub-AVAs."
def "wine:region:paso_robles" "AVA in San Luis Obispo County, California. Warm days, cool nights. Rhône varieties (Syrah, Grenache, Viognier) and Zinfandel. Emerging Cabernet Sauvignon zone."
def "wine:region:finger_lakes" "AVA in upstate New York. Continental climate moderated by deep glacial lakes. Riesling of international calibre. Also Gewurztraminer, Cabernet Franc, ice wines."

# ── Australia ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "wine:region:australia" "Wine-producing country. GI (Geographic Indication) system. South Australia dominant. Shiraz flagship; also Chardonnay, Riesling, Cabernet. Bold, fruit-forward style."
def "wine:region:barossa_valley" "GI in South Australia north of Adelaide. Warm continental climate. Old-vine Shiraz (some 150+ years). Grenache and Mourvèdre also significant. Home to Penfolds, Henschke."
def "wine:region:mclaren_vale" "GI in South Australia south of Adelaide. Mediterranean climate, diverse soils. Shiraz, Grenache, Cabernet Sauvignon. Known for dark, rich, fruit-driven reds."
def "wine:region:margaret_river" "GI in Western Australia. Maritime climate. World-class Cabernet Sauvignon-Merlot blends and Chardonnay. Leeuwin Estate, Vasse Felix, Cullen are benchmark producers."
def "wine:region:hunter_valley" "GI in New South Wales, oldest wine region in Australia. Semillon (unwooded, long-lived) and Shiraz. Hot, humid climate; vintage rain a challenge. Newcastle proximity."
def "wine:region:yarra_valley" "GI in Victoria near Melbourne. Cool climate. Pinot Noir and Chardonnay benchmark in Australia. De Bortoli, Yering Station, Coldstream Hills are key producers."

# ── New Zealand ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "wine:region:new_zealand" "Wine-producing country. GI system. Marlborough Sauvignon Blanc put NZ on the world map. Pinot Noir in Central Otago. Small production, high prices, quality-focused."
def "wine:region:marlborough" "GI at top of South Island, New Zealand. World's defining Sauvignon Blanc region. Wairau and Awatere sub-valleys. Intense, pungent, herbaceous style. 75% of NZ production."
def "wine:region:central_otago" "GI in inland South Island, NZ. World's southernmost commercial wine region. High altitude, continental climate. Pinot Noir of exceptional elegance and structure."
def "wine:region:hawkes_bay" "GI on North Island east coast, NZ. Warmest and driest NZ region. Gimblett Gravels sub-zone for Cabernet, Merlot, Syrah. Also fine Chardonnay."

# ── Argentina ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "wine:region:argentina" "Wine-producing country. IG (Indicación Geográfica) system. Mendoza dominant. High altitude (600-3000m) vineyards. Malbec is the flagship variety globally associated."
def "wine:region:mendoza" "IG region in western Argentina at Andes foothills. Argentina's premier wine region. Malbec, Cabernet Sauvignon, Chardonnay. Sub-regions: Luján de Cuyo, Maipú, Valle de Uco."
def "wine:region:salta_cafayate" "IG region in Salta province, northwestern Argentina. Torrontés (white aromatic) and Malbec. Cafayate Valley at 1700-3111m elevation. Among world's highest commercial vineyards."
def "wine:region:patagonia_wine" "IG in southern Argentina (Neuquén, Río Negro). Cool climate produces elegant Pinot Noir, Malbec, Sauvignon Blanc. Patagonian winds reduce disease pressure."

# ── Chile ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "wine:region:chile" "Wine-producing country. DO (Denominación de Origen) system. Long narrow geography creates diverse climates. Carménère rediscovered here 1994. Phylloxera-free country."
def "wine:region:maipo_valley" "DO region near Santiago, Chile. Classic Cabernet Sauvignon territory. Alto Maipo sub-zone (higher elevation) produces structured, age-worthy reds. Concha y Toro, Santa Rita."
def "wine:region:colchagua_valley" "DO region in O'Higgins, Chile. Warm climate. Carménère and Cabernet Sauvignon. Apalta sub-zone (Montes, Casa Lapostolle) is benchmark area."
def "wine:region:casablanca_valley" "DO region west of Santiago, Chile, near Pacific Ocean. Cool maritime climate. Chile's top Sauvignon Blanc, Chardonnay, and Pinot Noir. Fog influence from Humboldt Current."

# ── South Africa ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "wine:region:south_africa" "Wine-producing country. WO (Wine of Origin) system. Cape Winelands centred on Cape Town. Chenin Blanc (Steen) most planted; Pinotage unique variety. 350+ years of history."
def "wine:region:stellenbosch" "WO district in Western Cape, South Africa. Premium red wine region. Cabernet Sauvignon, Merlot, Shiraz, Chenin Blanc. University of Stellenbosch trains winemakers."
def "wine:region:franschhoek" "WO ward within Stellenbosch district. Huguenot heritage (French Protestants settled 1688). Semillon historically significant. Chardonnay, Cabernet; luxury wine tourism."
def "wine:region:swartland" "WO district north of Cape Town. Dry-farmed old vine Chenin Blanc and Rhône varieties on schist and granite. Natural wine movement epicentre. Eben Sadie, Mullineux key producers."

# ── Ancient/Historic ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

def "wine:region:georgia_country" "Wine-producing country in South Caucasus. One of world's oldest wine cultures (~6000 BCE). Qvevri clay jar winemaking is UNESCO heritage. Unique indigenous varieties."
def "wine:region:kakheti" "Main wine region of Georgia, eastern part. Produces 70% of Georgian wine. Rkatsiteli and Saperavi are key varieties. Traditional qvevri winemaking (skin-contact whites)."
def "wine:region:kartli_wine" "Wine region of Georgia, east of Tbilisi. One of world's oldest documented wine regions (~6000 BCE, Kvemo Kartli). Chinuri and Goruli Mtsvane white varieties."
def "wine:region:bekaa_valley" "Wine region in Lebanon, high-altitude valley between Mt. Lebanon and Anti-Lebanon ranges. 900-1000m elevation. Cinsault, Cabernet, Syrah. Château Musar is legendary producer."

